const e="alexander-rules-world",a="Adult Alexander the Great Rules the World",t=1,r="Alexander the Great, having conquered Persia at age 25, survives and turns his gaze to the rest of the known world. Explore the consequences of his continued rule.",n=["alexander-rules-world::n001"],s={"alexander-rules-world::n001":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n001",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"root",title:"Alexander Rules the Known World",summary:"At age 25, Alexander the Great has conquered the Persian Empire and controls a vast domain from Greece to the Indus River. He survives — and rules.",factuality:"speculative",sources:[{label:"Arrian: Anabasis of Alexander",url:"https://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/46976"},{label:"Plutarch: Life of Alexander",url:"https://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/14140"}],consequences:"This is the branching point — Alexander did not die in Babylon in 323 BC. Every path below explores what his continued rule meant for the ancient world. All downstream nodes are speculative or alternate history.",children:[{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n002",edgeType:"causal"},{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n003",edgeType:"causal"},{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n004",edgeType:"consequence"}],crossLinks:[]},"alexander-rules-world::n002":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n002",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"simple",title:"The Macedonian Empire Stabilizes",summary:"Alexander consolidates control over Persia, installing Macedonian governors and blending Persian administrative structures with Greek governance. The empire stops expanding and starts governing.",factuality:"historical",sources:[{label:"Diodorus Siculus: Library of History XVII",url:"https://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17A*.html"}],consequences:"A stable empire redirects military energy into infrastructure, trade, and cultural exchange. The Persian satrapy system is adapted rather than demolished.",children:[{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n005",edgeType:"causal"},{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n006",edgeType:"causal"}],crossLinks:[]},"alexander-rules-world::n003":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n003",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"simple",title:"Hellenism Accelerates Eastward",summary:"Greek language, philosophy, and art spread through Persia, Bactria, and northwest India. Local elites adopt Greek culture — some voluntarily, some by decree.",factuality:"historical",sources:[],consequences:"The fusion of Greek and Eastern cultures — Hellenism — would have produced philosophical and scientific advances centuries ahead of schedule. The Greek-Bactrian kingdoms show this was already happening at smaller scale.",children:[{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n006",edgeType:"causal"}],crossLinks:[]},"alexander-rules-world::n004":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n004",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"consequence",title:"Alexander Turns West — Rome and Carthage in His Sights",summary:"With the East secured, Alexander eyes the western Mediterranean. Ancient sources — Livy included — debated whether Rome could have withstood him. Preparations begin for a march on Carthage and Italy.",factuality:"speculative",sources:[],consequences:"Livy wrote that Alexander 'would have met his match' in Rome; others disagreed. His westward turn would have redrawn every Mediterranean power balance.",children:[{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n007",edgeType:"consequence"}],crossLinks:[]},"alexander-rules-world::n005":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n005",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"simple",title:"East–West Trade Routes Unify",summary:"Overland routes connecting Greece to Persia, Bactria, and India are formalized, taxed, and patrolled under Macedonian protection — an early, unified precursor to the Silk Road.",factuality:"historical",sources:[],consequences:null,children:[],crossLinks:[]},"alexander-rules-world::n006":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n006",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"simple",title:"A Macedonian Administrative Class Emerges",summary:"Both the stabilization of the empire (n002) and the spread of Hellenism (n003) converge here: a new governing class forms — Greek-educated, Persian-fluent administrators who serve as the backbone of a multi-ethnic Eurasian state.",factuality:"speculative",sources:[],consequences:"This class would have been history's first truly cosmopolitan bureaucracy, predating the Roman civil service by centuries and operating at continental scale.",children:[{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n008",edgeType:"causal"},{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n009",edgeType:"causal"}],crossLinks:[]},"alexander-rules-world::n007":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n007",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"simple",title:"Alexander Defeats Rome — The Republic Falls",summary:"Macedonian phalanxes overwhelm the Roman legions on Italian soil. The Roman Republic, still a regional Italian power, is dissolved. Alexander installs a client administration in Latium.",factuality:"alternate",sources:[],consequences:null,children:[],crossLinks:[]},"alexander-rules-world::n008":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n008",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"consequence",title:"Alexandria Becomes the Intellectual Capital of the World",summary:"The Library of Alexandria expands under royal patronage. Scholars from India, Persia, Egypt, and Greece congregate. Mathematics, medicine, and engineering advance at an unprecedented pace.",factuality:"speculative",sources:[],consequences:"A sustained intellectual renaissance under a unified Eurasian empire could have produced a proto-industrial revolution by the 1st century BC — steam power, advanced astronomy, systematic medicine.",children:[{targetId:"alexander-rules-world::n010",edgeType:"consequence"}],crossLinks:[]},"alexander-rules-world::n009":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n009",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"simple",title:"Eastern Provinces Experiment with Elected Councils",summary:"The administrative class, drawing on Athenian democratic tradition and Persian civic custom, introduces proto-democratic governance in the eastern provinces. Local councils handle taxation and disputes.",factuality:"alternate",sources:[],consequences:null,children:[],crossLinks:[]},"alexander-rules-world::n010":{id:"alexander-rules-world::n010",narration:"alexander-rules-world",type:"consequence",title:"A Unified Eurasian Empire Endures Beyond the Ancient World",summary:"The Macedonian world-state, spanning from Gibraltar to the Indus, persists into what would have been the Common Era. The fragmentation of the medieval world — the fall of Rome, the Dark Ages — becomes a path never taken.",factuality:"alternate",sources:[],consequences:"If this empire endured, the rise of Christianity, Islam, and the medieval nation-state might all be erased or transformed beyond recognition. The 'Common Era' itself might carry a different name.",children:[],crossLinks:[{targetNodeId:"napoleon-wins-waterloo::n001",label:"What if Napoleon, too, survived to rule a continent-spanning empire? (Coming Soon)"}]}},l={slug:e,title:a,version:1,description:r,rootNodeIds:n,nodes:s};export{l as default,r as description,s as nodes,n as rootNodeIds,e as slug,a as title,t as version};
